  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Building Resilience and Providing Child Protection Services through Family Preservation, Community Engagement, and Systems Strengthening.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Tdh is proposing to implement a 9-month Child Protection project which focusses on the provision of life-saving child-sensitive and youth-friendly interventions to the most vulnerable children and adolescents who are at risk of violence, exploitation, abuse, and neglect. Most of these separated and unaccompanied children are living in the poorest households in Dikwa and Pulka. The proposed intervention is expected to reach a total of 3,160 girls and boys with integrated case management, structured and non-structured Psychosocial Support (PSS) and community-based services. Additionally, 2,180 women and men will directly benefit from capacity building, child protection mainstreaming and community outreach sessions. This project will contribute to improving girls&#x2019; and boys&#x2019; access to quality child protection services in Dikwa and Pulka. In line with the NHF 2019 allocation strategy, the project aims to provide first-line emergency lifesaving assistance to the children, caregivers, and their families through the provision of comprehensive child protection services. The project also aims to strengthen the resilience of the children, families, community and their environment through family preservation programs, engaging communities and strengthening the community-based child protection system. 

The project consists of major components as listed below: 

a) Comprehensive child protection case management services
b) structured and unstructured psychosocial support for children and their caregivers 
c) strengthening of community-based child protection mechanisms 
d) child protection mainstreaming into other humanitarian sectors  
e) Raise the profile of child protection through awareness, sensitization, and events

In addition to direct child protection services to the children, the project will aim to strengthen the child protection systems at the community and family level for prevention and response to violence, abuse, and exploitation of children. Wherever feasible, the project will make strong efforts to engage relevant Government Authorities in support of this project. This, to some extent, will ensure the sustainability of the actions.

Pulka and Dikwa are considered to be high mine risk areas. To improve the protective environment of the children in project locations TdH will coordinate with Mine Action Group (MAG) to provide Mine Risk Education to the children attending PSS sessions and the volunteers from the community.  The main objective of Mine Risk Education is to reduce the risk of death or injury from mines/IED/ERW, through raising awareness and changing behavior.</narrative>
  </description>
